results.definition: Unexpectedly sudden:  an abrupt change in the weather.
The state of being away.
To take (something) in through or as through pores or interstices.
The act or process of absorbing or the condition of being absorbed.
Occurring in or marked by abundance; plentiful. See Synonyms at plentiful.
Of, relating to, or characteristic of a school, especially one of higher learning.
To answer affirmatively:  accept an invitation.
A means of approaching, entering, exiting, communicating with, or making use of:  a store with easy access.
Easily approached or entered.
To be or go with as a companion.
To succeed in doing; bring to pass. See Synonyms at perform.
A narrative or record of events.
Conformity to fact.
Conforming exactly to fact; errorless.
To admit the existence, reality, or truth of.
To gain possession of:  acquire 100 shares of stock.
The state or fact of being actual; reality. See Synonyms at existence.
Quickness, accuracy, and keenness of judgment or insight.
A supporter, as of a cause or individual:  a vote that pleased adherents of education reform.
The coming or arrival, especially of something extremely important:  the advent of the computer.
To speak, plead, or argue in favor of. See Synonyms at support.
To have an influence on or effect a change in:  Inflation affects the buying power of the dollar.
To parcel out; distribute or apportion:  allotting land to homesteaders; allot blame.
To place in a friendly association, as by treaty:  Italy allied itself with Germany during World War II.
To occur in a successive manner:  day alternating with night.
The choice between two mutually exclusive possibilities.
The height of a thing above a reference level, especially above sea level or above the earth's surface. See Synonyms at elevation.
Open to more than one interpretation:  an ambiguous reply.
To make or become better; improve. See Synonyms at improve.
Similarity in some respects between things that are otherwise dissimilar.
To examine methodically by separating into parts and studying their interrelations.
Recurring, done, or performed every year; yearly:  an annual medical examination.
To bring peace, quiet, or calm to; soothe.
Possible to estimate, measure, or perceive:  appreciable changes in temperature.  See Synonyms at perceptible.
Suitable for a particular person, condition, occasion, or place; fitting.
A quality that can be perceived by the olfactory sense:  the aroma of garlic and onions.  See Synonyms at smell.
The act or process of arranging:  the arrangement of a time and place for the meeting.
Having or displaying a sense of overbearing self-worth or self-importance.
The act or process of rising or going upward.
Expulsion of breath in speech.
To have a great ambition or ultimate goal; desire strongly:  aspired to stardom.
To estimate the value of (property) for taxation.
To make (something burdensome or painful) less intense or severe:  assuage her grief.  See Synonyms at relieve.
Of or relating to hearing, the organs of hearing, or the sense of hearing.
Severe or stern in disposition or appearance; somber and grave:  the austere figure of a Puritan minister.
Conforming to fact and therefore worthy of trust, reliance, or belief:  an authentic account by an eyewitness.
Immoderate desire for wealth; cupidity.
To affirm positively; declare.
Drearily commonplace and often predictable; trite: "Blunt language cannot hide a banal conception”  ( James Wolcott).
To behave as a friend to.
To give a false representation to; misrepresent: "He spoke roughly in order to belie his air of gentility”  ( James Joyce).
To accept as true or real:  Do you believe the news stories?
Producing or promoting a favorable result; advantageous.
Something that promotes or enhances well-being; an advantage:  The field trip was of great benefit to the students.
Of a kind and gentle disposition.
An account of a person's life written, composed, or produced by another:  a film biography of Adlai Stevenson; an oral biography.
The science of life and of living organisms, including their structure, function, growth, origin, evolution, and distribution. It includes botany and zoology and all their subdivisions.
Unpleasantly loud and noisy: "There are those who find the trombones blatant and the triangle silly, but both add effective color”  ( Musical Heritage Review).  See Synonyms at vociferous.
The quality or state of being brief in duration.
An upright, cupboardlike repository with shelves, drawers, or compartments for the safekeeping or display of objects.
Pathology   An abnormal concretion in the body, usually formed of mineral salts and found in the gallbladder, kidney, or urinary bladder, for example.
A slender grooved lead bar used to hold together the panes in stained glass or latticework windows.
A series of military operations undertaken to achieve a large-scale objective during a war:  Grant's Vicksburg campaign secured the entire Mississippi for the Union.
Free from prejudice; impartial.
Angular deviation from a vertical or horizontal plane or surface; an inclination or slope.
Occurring by chance. See Synonyms at chance.
Of, involving, or constituting a cause:  a causal relationship between scarcity of goods and higher prices.
Being a feature that helps to distinguish a person or thing; distinctive:  heard my friend's characteristic laugh; the stripes that are characteristic of the zebra.
To describe the qualities or peculiarities of:  characterized the warden as ruthless.
An action or influence that stops motion or expression; a restraint:  Heavy rains were a check on the army's advance.
Of or relating to a chorus or choir.
The boundary line of a circle.
To quote as an authority or example.
To make clear or easier to understand; elucidate:  clarified her intentions.
Appealing to the intellect or powers of reasoning; convincing:  a cogent argument.  See Synonyms at valid.
Occupying the same area in space or happening at the same time:  a series of coincident events.  See Synonyms at contemporary.
Assembled into or viewed as a whole.
The act or process of colliding; a crash or conflict.
A series of explanations or interpretations.
To travel as a commuter.
The act of comparing or the process of being compared.
The state or quality of being adequately or well qualified; ability. See Synonyms at ability.
Properly or sufficiently qualified; capable:  a competent typist.
Of, involving, or determined by competition:  competitive games.
One that competes with another, as in sports or business; a rival.
Contented to a fault; self-satisfied and unconcerned:  He had become complacent after years of success.
Consisting of interconnected or interwoven parts; composite.
A constituent element, as of a system. See Synonyms at element.
The act or fact of grasping the meaning, nature, or importance of; understanding.
So large in scope or content as to include much:  a comprehensive history of the revolution.
To determine by mathematics, especially by numerical methods:  computed the tax due.  See Synonyms at calculate.
To acknowledge, often reluctantly, as being true, just, or proper; admit. See Synonyms at acknowledge.
Serving to put an end to doubt, question, or uncertainty; decisive. See Synonyms at decisive.
Trust or faith in a person or thing.
Similarity in form or character; agreement:  I acted in conformity with my principles.
To come face to face with, especially with defiance or hostility:  I wish to confront my accuser in a court of law.
The awareness of a moral or ethical aspect to one's conduct together with the urge to prefer right over wrong:  Let your conscience be your guide.
Having an awareness of one's environment and one's own existence, sensations, and thoughts. See Synonyms at aware.
Following one after another without interruption; successive:  was absent on three consecutive days; won five consecutive games on the road.

An opinion or position reached by a group as a whole: "Among political women . . . there is a clear consensus about the problems women candidates have traditionally faced”  ( Wendy Kaminer).  See Usage Note at redundancy.
The body of voters or the residents of a district represented by an elected legislator or official.
The act or process of consuming.
Belonging to the same period of time:  a fact documented by two contemporary sources.
Manifesting or feeling contempt; scornful.
Uninterrupted in time, sequence, substance, or extent. See Synonyms at continual.
The act of contradicting.
Involving, of the nature of, or being a contradiction. See Synonyms at opposite.
The act of contributing.
To exercise authoritative or dominating influence over; direct. See Synonyms at conduct.
The quality of being suitable to one's comfort, purposes, or needs:  the convenience of living near shops, schools, and libraries.
The act of converting.
The act or process of corrupting.
A preparation, such as powder or a skin cream, designed to beautify the body by direct application.
Pertinent or common to the whole world:  an issue of cosmopolitan import.
Onward movement in a particular direction; progress:  the course of events.
Polite behavior.
Acceptance as true or valid; belief. See Synonyms at belief.
A critical review or commentary, especially one dealing with works of art or literature.

Believing or showing the belief that people are motivated chiefly by base or selfish concerns; skeptical of the motives of others:  a cynical dismissal of the politician's promise to reform the campaign finance system.
The act or practice of deceiving; deception.

A linear array of digits that represents a real number, every decimal place indicating a multiple of a negative power of 10. For example, the decimal 0.1 =  1/10 , 0.12 =  12/100 , 0.003 =  3/1000 . Also called decimal fraction.
Marked by defiance; boldly resisting.
The quality of being delicate.
The way in which a person behaves; deportment.
To show clearly and deliberately; manifest:  demonstrated her skill as a gymnast; demonstrate affection by hugging.
Mathematics   The expression written below the line in a common fraction that indicates the number of parts into which one whole is divided.
The condition or quality of being deep.
Resulting from or employing derivation:  a derivative word; a derivative process.
To prevent or discourage from acting, as by means of fear or doubt: "Does negotiated disarmament deter war?”  ( Edward Teller).  See Synonyms at dissuade.
To diminish or impair in quality, character, or value:  Time and neglect had deteriorated the property.
Precisely limited or defined; definite:  a determinate number; a determinate distance.
To draw or take away; divert:  They could detract little from so solid an argument.
Damage, harm, or loss:  took a long leave of absence without detriment to her career.  See Synonyms at disadvantage.
To distinguish or identify (a disease, for example) by diagnosis.
A conversation between two or more people.
The quality or condition of being unlike or dissimilar.
Lacking or marked by a lack of self-confidence; shy and timid. See Synonyms at shy1.
The art or practice of conducting international relations, as in negotiating alliances, treaties, and agreements.
To fail to correspond:  our figures disagree.  See Synonyms at differ.
To pass out of sight; vanish.
To sever or interrupt the connection of or between:  disconnected the hose.
To notice or learn, especially by making an effort:  got home and discovered that the furnace wasn't working.
Consideration of a subject by a group; an earnest conversation.
Free of bias and self-interest; impartial: "disinterested scientific opinion on fluorides in the water supply”  ( Ellen R. Shell).
To rid one's mind of:  managed to dispel my doubts.
To pay no attention or heed to; ignore.
To subject (a substance) to distillation.
The act of distinguishing; differentiation.
Differing one from another.
The fact or quality of being diverse; difference.
Capable of being divided, especially with no remainder:  15 is divisible by 3 and 5.
Fraught with uncertainty or doubt; undecided.
Deliberate deceptiveness in behavior or speech.
Continuance or persistence in time.
Zestfully enthusiastic.
Departing from a recognized, conventional, or established norm or pattern. See Synonyms at strange.
An article in a publication expressing the opinion of its editors or publishers.
To bring or draw out (something latent); educe.
To rise from or as if from immersion:  Sea mammals must emerge periodically to breathe.
The act or process of emerging.
A position of great distinction or superiority:  rose to eminence as a surgeon.
Of high rank, station, or quality; noteworthy:  eminent members of the community.
To give or send out (matter or energy):  isotopes that emit radioactive particles; a stove emitting heat.
Special forcefulness of expression that gives importance to something singled out; stress:  a lecture on housekeeping with emphasis on neatness; paused for emphasis, then announced the winner's name.
To give emphasis to; stress.
A person who works for another in return for financial or other compensation.
To inspire with hope, courage, or confidence; hearten.
To weaken or destroy the strength or vitality of: "the luxury which enervates and destroys nations”  ( Henry David Thoreau).  See Synonyms at deplete.
To make greater, as in value, beauty, or effectiveness; augment.
Very great in size, extent, number, or degree.

To have, impose, or require as a necessary accompaniment or consequence:  The investment entailed a high risk. The proposition X is a rose entails the proposition X is a flower because all roses are flowers.
Equal, as in value, force, or meaning.
Open to two or more interpretations and often intended to mislead; ambiguous. See Synonyms at ambiguous.
Containing or derived from error; mistaken:  erroneous conclusions.
Characterized by erudition; learned. See Synonyms at learned.
The intrinsic or indispensable properties that serve to characterize or identify something.
A gradual process in which something changes into a different and usually more complex or better form. See Synonyms at development.
To represent as greater than is actually the case; overstate:  exaggerate the size of the enemy force; exaggerated his own role in the episode.
To extend beyond or outside of:  The river exceeded its banks.
To do or be better than; surpass.
Of the highest or finest quality; exceptionally good of its kind.
The state of exceeding what is normal or sufficient:  rains that filled the reservoirs to excess.
Requiring immediate action or remedy. See Synonyms at urgent.
The fact or state of existing; being.
To increase the size, volume, quantity, or scope of; enlarge:  expanded her store by adding a second room.  See Synonyms at increase.
The act or process of expanding:  the new nation's expansion westward.
To look forward to the probable occurrence or appearance of:  expecting a telephone call; expects rain on Sunday.
Something spent to attain a goal or accomplish a purpose:  an expense of time and energy on the project.
Fully and clearly expressed; leaving nothing implied.
A release of mechanical, chemical, or nuclear energy in a sudden and often violent manner with the generation of high temperature and usually with the release of gases.
A setting forth of meaning or intent.
The act or an instance of exposing, as:
Large in extent, range, or amount.
Relating to, existing on, or connected with the outside or an outer part; exterior.
Not constituting a vital element or part.
Beyond what is ordinary or usual:  extraordinary authority.
Playfully jocular; humorous:  facetious remarks.
Ease in moving, acting, or doing; aptitude: "an extreme facility in acquiring new dialects”  ( W.H. Hudson).
Containing or based on a fallacy:  a fallacious assumption.
A false notion.
Possessing or displaying careful, meticulous attention to detail.
Of, relating to, or involving finance, finances, or financiers.
To estimate or calculate in advance, especially to predict (weather conditions) by analysis of meteorological data. See Synonyms at predict.
Located away from one's native country:  on business in a foreign city.
Deliberation, consideration, or planning beforehand.
To abstain from; relinquish:  unwilling to forgo dessert.
The act or process of forming something or of taking form.
The property or condition of occurring at frequent intervals.
Of or relating to the foundation or base; elementary:  the fundamental laws of the universe.
More distant in degree, time, or space:  a result that was further from our expectations than last time; the further lamppost.
To stimulate or shock with an electric current.
Given to excessive and often trivial or rambling talk; tiresomely talkative.
A standard or scale of measurement.
Relating to or descriptive of an entire group or class; general. See Synonyms at general.
The solid surface of the earth.
To predict (a result or an event) without sufficient information.
Exhibiting accord in feeling or action.
The act of hindering.
Generating electricity by conversion of the energy of running water.
The side of a right triangle opposite the right angle.
A tentative explanation for an observation, phenomenon, or scientific problem that can be tested by further investigation.
Not legible or decipherable.
Contradicting or disregarding the principles of logic.
To provide or brighten with light.
Extremely large; huge.
Unshakably calm and collected. See Synonyms at cool.
Implied or understood though not directly expressed:  an implicit agreement not to raise the touchy subject.
To involve by logical necessity; entail:  Life implies growth and death.
Not suited to circumstances or needs; unsuitable:  improper shoes for a hike; improper medical treatment.
The quality of being offensively bold.
To relate to a particular cause or source; attribute the fault or responsibility to:  imputed the rocket failure to a faulty gasket; kindly imputed my clumsiness to inexperience.
Not accessible; remote or unapproachable.
Mistaken or incorrect; not accurate.
Not duly attentive.
Uttered without the use of normal words or syllables; incomprehensible as speech or language: "a cry . . . that . . . sank down into an inarticulate whine”  ( Jack London).
The condition or quality of being incoherent.
Lacking cohesion, connection, or harmony; not coherent:  incoherent fragments of a story.
Incapable of associating or blending or of being associated or blended because of disharmony, incongruity, or antagonism:  incompatible views on religion.
Not complete.
Impossible to comprehend or grasp fully:  inconceivable folly; an inconceivable disaster.
Not convenient, especially:
Originating and living or occurring naturally in an area or environment. See Synonyms at native.
Characterized by or filled with indignation. See Synonyms at angry.
Not apt or fitting; inappropriate.
Impossible to avoid or prevent. See Synonyms at certain.
The act or process of deriving logical conclusions from premises known or assumed to be true.

A power affecting a person, thing, or course of events, especially one that operates without any direct or apparent effort:  relaxed under the influence of the music; the influence of television on modern life.
Marked by inventive skill and imagination.
An element in a mixture or compound. See Synonyms at element.
Existing as an essential constituent or characteristic; intrinsic.
To set going by taking the first step; begin:  initiated trade with developing nations.  See Synonyms at begin.
Difficult to fathom or understand; impenetrable. See Synonyms at mysterious.
The capacity to discern the true nature of a situation; penetration.
Not significant, especially:
Presumptuous and insulting in manner or speech; arrogant.
An example that is cited to prove or invalidate a contention or illustrate a point. See Synonyms at example.
An almost imperceptible space of time. See Synonyms at moment.
To introduce by gradual, persistent efforts; implant: "Morality . . . may be instilled into their minds”  ( Thomas Jefferson).
Not sufficient; inadequate.
Of, relating to, or constituting an island.
Of or relating to the intellect.
The capacity to acquire and apply knowledge.
Of, relating to, or characterized by intensity:  intensive training.  See Usage Note at intense.
To act on each other: "More than a dozen variable factors could interact, with their permutations running into the thousands”  ( Tom Clancy).
To stop, deflect, or interrupt the progress or intended course of:  intercepted me with a message as I was leaving.
Lying or occurring between two extremes or in a middle position or state:  an aircraft having an intermediate range; an intermediate school.
Being or seeming to be without an end; endless. See Synonyms at continual.
To cut across or through:  The path intersects the park.
Of, relating to, or constituting an introduction.
One who is incapacitated by a chronic illness or disability.
One who is incapacitated by a chronic illness or disability.
Of inestimable value; priceless:  invaluable paintings; invaluable help.
To contain as a part; include.
Immune to attack; impregnable.
The use of words to express something different from and often opposite to their literal meaning.
Unrelated to the matter being considered.
To set apart or cut off from others.
The act or process of judging; the formation of an opinion after consideration or deliberation.
Having or exhibiting sound judgment; prudent.
Full of juice; succulent.
The act of justifying.
Of, relating to, or situated at or on the side.
Deserving commendation; praiseworthy.
Expressing or conferring praise:  a laudatory review of the new play.
Being in compliance with the law; lawful:  a legitimate business.
The period of time during which an individual is alive.
Possessing or displaying the qualities or characteristics that make something probable:  They are likely to become angry with him.
Of, relating to, or resembling a line; straight.
The body of written works of a language, period, or culture.
Of, relating to, or characterized by litigation.
The study of the principles of reasoning, especially of the structure of propositions as distinguished from their content and of method and validity in deductive reasoning.
Of, relating to, in accordance with, or of the nature of logic.
Easily understood; intelligible.
Producing wealth; profitable:  a lucrative income; a lucrative marketing strategy.
Present participle of lie1.
Machines or machine parts considered as a group.
Greatness of rank or position: "such duties as were expected of a landowner of his magnitude”  ( Anthony Powell).
To keep up or carry on; continue:  maintain good relations.
The act of maintaining or the state of being maintained.
Capable of being shaped or formed, as by hammering or pressure:  a malleable metal.
A person, an enterprise, or an entity that manufactures something.
Of or relating to the sea:  marine exploration.
Possession of consummate skill.
The substance or substances out of which a thing is or can be made.
The branch of physics that is concerned with the analysis of the action of forces on matter or material systems.
The science of diagnosing, treating, or preventing disease and other damage to the body or mind.
Relating or belonging to the Middle Ages.

Any of a category of electropositive elements that usually have a shiny surface, are generally good conductors of heat and electricity, and can be melted or fused, hammered into thin sheets, or drawn into wires. Typical metals form salts with nonmetals, basic oxides with oxygen, and alloys with one another.
Extremely careful and precise.
The smaller in number of two groups forming a whole.
A unit of time equal to one sixtieth of an hour, or 60 seconds.
Improper, unlawful, or incorrect use; misapplication.
Being in or conforming to the prevailing or current fashion; stylish. See Synonyms at fashionable.
Government by a monarch.
Of or relating to money.
Of, relating to, or typical of this world; secular.
Of, relating to, or typical of a municipality.
Very liberal in giving; generous.
A narrated account; a story.
Absolutely essential. See Synonyms at indispensable.
To make ineffective or invalid; nullify.
Not aligned with, supporting, or favoring either side in a war, dispute, or contest.
Of or relating to a number or series of numbers:  numerical order.
Of or having to do with a material object.
No longer in use:  an obsolete word.
The action, fact, or instance of occurring.
Having a distinctive odor:  odorous jasmine flowers; odorous garbage.
From a place or position:  drove off.
Of, relating to, or contributing to the sense of smell.
The capacity to know everything.
Having total knowledge; knowing everything:  an omniscient deity; the omniscient narrator.
An onslaught; an assault.
Impenetrable by light; neither transparent nor translucent.
A belief or conclusion held with confidence but not substantiated by positive knowledge or proof: "The world is not run by thought, nor by imagination, but by opinion”  ( Elizabeth Drew).
A favorable or advantageous circumstance or combination of circumstances.
Placed or located directly across from something else or from each other:  opposite sides of a building.
The point at which something comes into existence or from which it derives or is derived.
Preceding all others in time; first.
Adhering to the accepted or traditional and established faith, especially in religion.
The quality or state of being orthodox.
Used to indicate obligation or duty:  You ought to work harder than that.
To leave behind; outrun.
Being an equal distance apart everywhere:  dancers in two parallel rows.  See Usage Note at absolute.
The quality or condition of being parallel; a parallel relationship.
A restatement of a text or passage in another form or other words, often to clarify meaning.
To take part in something:  participated in the festivities.
A fervent, sometimes militant supporter or proponent of a party, cause, faction, person, or idea.
Receiving or subjected to an action without responding or initiating an action in return:  the mind viewed as a passive receptacle for sensory experience.  See Synonyms at inactive.
Smallness of number; fewness.
A person traveling on foot; a walker.
To become aware of directly through any of the senses, especially sight or hearing.
The process, act, or faculty of perceiving.
To begin and carry through to completion; do:  The surgeon performed the operation.
Lasting or remaining without essential change: "the universal human yearning for something permanent, enduring, without shadow of change”  ( Willa Cather).
Steady persistence in adhering to a course of action, a belief, or a purpose; steadfastness.
Of or relating to a particular person; private: "Like their personal lives, women's history is fragmented, interrupted”  ( Elizabeth Janeway).
The quality or condition of being a person.
A view or vista.

To induce to undertake a course of action or embrace a point of view by means of argument, reasoning, or entreaty: "to make children fit to live in a society by persuading them to learn and accept its codes”  ( Alan W. Watts).  See Usage Note at convince.
The act of perturbing.
Having the quality or tendency to pervade or permeate:  the pervasive odor of garlic.
An occurrence, circumstance, or fact that is perceptible by the senses.
To speculate in a philosophical manner.
Love and pursuit of wisdom by intellectual means and moral self-discipline.
Of or relating to phlegm; phlegmy.
Of or relating to phonetics.
A scientist who specializes in physics.
A thing considered as a unit or an element of a larger thing, quantity, or class; a portion:  a piece of string.
Seemingly or apparently valid, likely, or acceptable; credible:  a plausible excuse.
One who writes plays; a dramatist.
Giving or affording pleasure or enjoyment; agreeable:  a pleasant scene; pleasant sensations.
Of or relating to a pole.
A place or location.
Characterized by or displaying certainty, acceptance, or affirmation:  a positive answer; positive criticism.
To have as property; own.
Capable of happening, existing, or being true without contradicting proven facts, laws, or circumstances.
Capable of being but not yet in existence; latent:  a potential problem.
Dangerously lacking in security or stability:  a precarious posture; precarious footing on the ladder.
The fact, state, or right of preceding; priority:  Applications arriving first will receive precedence.
Clearly expressed or delineated; definite:  The victim gave a precise description of the suspect.
To make impossible, as by action taken in advance; prevent. See Synonyms at prevent.
One who precedes another in time, especially in holding an office or position.
To state, tell about, or make known in advance, especially on the basis of special knowledge.
The act of predicting.
the status of being preeminent, dominant or ascendant
To choose or be in the habit of choosing as more desirable or as having more value:  prefers coffee to tea.
The selecting of someone or something over another or others.
An adverse judgment or opinion formed beforehand or without knowledge or examination of the facts.
The act or process of preparing.
Of or relating to prescience.
The condition of being prevalent.
Widely or commonly occurring, existing, accepted, or practiced. See Synonyms at prevailing.
First, highest, or foremost in importance, rank, worth, or degree; chief. See Synonyms at chief.
A basic truth, law, or assumption:  the principles of democracy.
Remaining in a pure state; uncorrupted by civilization.
An exploratory action, expedition, or device, especially one designed to investigate and obtain information on a remote or unknown region.
A manner of proceeding; a way of performing or effecting something:  standard procedure.
To go forward or onward, especially after an interruption; continue:  proceeded to his destination; paused to clear her throat, then proceeded.
An occupation or career: "One of the highest compliments a child can pay a parent is to choose his or her profession”  ( Joan Nathan).
A side view of an object or structure, especially of the human head.
The process of progressing; progress.
The quality or condition of being prominent.
The systematic propagation of a doctrine or cause or of information reflecting the views and interests of those advocating such a doctrine or cause.
To cause to move forward or onward. See Synonyms at push.
Of or resulting from divine providence.
To describe by enumerating the characteristics or qualities of; characterize.
A specified or indefinite number or amount.
One of four equal parts.
A response to a stimulus.
Prepared or available for service, action, or progress:  I am ready to work. The soup will be ready in a minute. The pupils are ready to learn to read.
To know to be something that has been perceived before:  recognize a face.
To consider again, especially with intent to alter or modify a previous decision.
Exceeding what is necessary or natural; superfluous.
To direct to a source for help or information:  referred her to a heart specialist; referred me to his last employer for a recommendation.
The act or an instance of refusing.
To prove to be false or erroneous; overthrow by argument or proof:  refute testimony.
Having a bearing on or connection with the matter at hand.
The act of relying or the state of being reliant.
Unwilling; disinclined:  reluctant to help.
The act or process or an instance of repeating or being repeated.
To produce a counterpart, image, or copy of.
The act or an instance of resisting or the capacity to resist.
Giving or given as an answer; responsive.
The state or quality of being reticent; reserve.
Inclined to keep one's thoughts, feelings, and personal affairs to oneself. See Synonyms at silent.
Looking back on, contemplating, or directed to the past.
The art or study of using language effectively and persuasively.
In widespread existence, practice, or use; increasingly prevalent.
Of or relating to basic facts or principles; elementary.
Of the color of blood; red.
Not domesticated or cultivated; wild:  savage beasts of the jungle.
Of, relating to, or characteristic of scholars or scholarship:  scholarly pursuits; a scholarly edition with footnotes.  See Synonyms at learned.
The range of one's perceptions, thoughts, or actions.
A public clerk or secretary, especially in ancient times.
The act of seceding.
Material that settles to the bottom of a liquid; lees.
Any of the faculties by which stimuli from outside or inside the body are received and felt, as the faculties of hearing, sight, smell, touch, taste, and equilibrium.
Capable of perceiving with a sense or senses.
A grammatical unit that is syntactically independent and has a subject that is expressed or, as in imperative sentences, understood and a predicate that contains at least one finite verb.
To set or keep apart; disunite.
A following of one thing after another; succession.
Employment in duties or work for another, as for a government:  has been in the company's service for 15 years.
The state or quality of being significant. See Synonyms at importance.
Having or expressing a meaning; meaningful.
Related in appearance or nature; alike though not identical.
To make simple or simpler, as:
To have or take on the appearance, form, or sound of; imitate.
